In TypeScript, you can handle situations where you know that a value may have multiple types theoretically but want to restrict it to a single type in practice using type assertions. Type assertions allow you to inform the TypeScript compiler about certain constraints on your types, even if those constraints are just based on your own assumptions or best guesses.

Here is an example to illustrate this concept:

```typescript
// Define a function that accepts a string, an integer, and a boolean
function processValue(value: string | number | boolean): void {
    const str = value as string;
    const int = Number(value);
    const isTrue = (value === true);

    console.log(str); // Outputs: 'true'
    console.log(int);   // Outputs: 1
    console.log(isTrue); // Outputs: true
}

// Example usage
processValue(true); // Outputs: true
processValue(42);    // Outputs: 42
processValue(false); // Outputs: false
processValue(123);    // Outputs: 123

// Type assertion to ensure only a boolean type is allowed
type assertion:
processValue(value: boolean): void {
    if (typeof value!== boolean) {
        throw new Error('Type assertion is not allowed');
    }
}

// This will throw an error because type assertion is not allowed
type assertion:
processValue(value: string | number | boolean): void;
```

In this example, `type assertion` is used to enforce the constraint that `value` must be a boolean. If you try to pass a string, number, or any other type, TypeScript will throw an error because the type assertion is not allowed.

Type assertions can be useful for situations where you have certain constraints on the type that you want to enforce in practice, but you don't have a way to enforce them statically. However, they should be used sparingly and only when you have a clear and justified reason for them.

Keep in mind that type assertions are not part of the TypeScript standard library, so you need to define them yourself or use third-party solutions if you need more advanced type checking features.

